article.description:
ari Phillips scored 15 points, 10 in the first
half, as New York won its fourth consecutive game with a
73-52 victory Monday night over the Cleveland Rockers.
article.headline: New York puts four into double figures
article.linkText: New York beats Cleveland to claim fourth in a row
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- Tari Phillips scored 15 points, 10 in the first
half, as New York won its fourth consecutive game with a
73-52 victory Monday night over the Cleveland Rockers.

	   Vickie Johnson followed with 14 points for the Liberty, one more than Tamika
Whitmore, the WNBA player of the week. Teresa Weatherspoon added a
season-high 10 points for New York (14-9), which has won six of
eight.

	   The Liberty is perfect in four games since the All-Star break
after entering it having lost seven of 11.

	   ''The big difference for the team since the break is that we
went back to fundamentals both on defense and offense,'' coach
Richie Adubato said. ''The basics win the games for you.''

	   It was the Liberty's first victory over Cleveland this season in
three tries.

	   Merlakia Jones scored 11 points for the Rockers (8-14), who have
lost eight of nine. Chasity Melvin added 10 points, but Cleveland
only shot 35.7 percent from the field (20 of 56).

	   ''The last two games our shooting has been horrendous,'' coach
Dan Hughes said. ''We have to get people to step up, and we have to
get some balance.''

	   The Rockers fell seven games behind Eastern Conference-leading
Washington. It is the first time Cleveland is not the thick of
playoff contention.

	   ''There's still an opportunity to do it, but we have to find a
way to get back in it,'' Hughes said. ''Right now, we're not
winning the close games.''

	   Robinson made a basket to start a 7-2 run that gave the Liberty
a 14-9 lead at 12:06.

	   Penny Taylor made two foul shots to cut it to 14-11, but
Robinson made a jumper and two free throws, and Becky Hammon hit a
3-pointer during a 15-0 run that gave the Liberty a 26-11 lead at
4:34.

	   Phillips made a layup, and Johnson hit a jumper in the last 12
seconds of the first half to give New York a 37-18 lead.

	   Whitmore opened the second half with a jumper to make it 39-18,
but Cleveland went on a 9-3 run to close within 42-27 at 16:12.

	   New York answered with an 11-4 spurt, behind Robinson's
3-pointer, to make it 53-31 at 12:05.

	   New York let a big lead get away in its last game against
Indiana, and struggled to an eight-point victory. They didn't want
the same thing to happen Monday night.

	   ''We warned our team that the first four minutes of the half
were crucial,'' Adubato said. ''I reminded them what happened at
Indiana when we let them back in the game. Fortunately, we were
able to build it back up.''
